@node engOverall "Xhess overall"
The game "Xhess" is based upon the board game chess. However, the main
difference is that the 8×8 squares in Xhess are further divided into 2×2 smaller
squares each. Instead of normal chess pieces, the game uses small component-
style pieces, which can be either moved normally or united into groups, which
can be moved like standard chess pieces. More information is available in the
@{"Playing the game" link "engPlay"} and @{"Pieces" link "engPieces"} nodes.
@endnode

@node engPlay "Playing Xhess"
Xhess is a game for two players. Player 1 starts from the top, with the blue
pieces. Player 2 starts from the bottom, with the green pieces. On his/her
turn, a player can either move a single piece, move a group of pieces, or buy a
new piece.
When you first start the program, you will see the logo picture. Choose "New" or
"Load" from the Game menu to start a new game. You will then see a 16×16-square
chess board. Playing the game is done by clicking the mouse on this board.
To move a single piece, click on it and it will be selected. To move it into
another square, click on the destination square. Single pieces only move one
square in any direction, regardless of type and ownership. Single pieces cannot
"take" other pieces.
To move a group of pieces, click on the centre of the 2×2-square area (outlined
in yellow) to select the group. You can only select groups in which your pieces
have a non-minority position (that is, there are at least as many of your pieces
than there are of the opponent's pieces). To move the group, click on the
destination area of 2×2 squares. Note that if you are moving a group which has
both your pieces and your opponent's pieces, the opponent's pieces move too.
Groups of pieces can "take" other groups by moving into their 2×2-square areas.
You will be given a monetary reward for "taking" your opponent's pieces, this
can be used to purchase new pieces.
Details on the pieces is available in the @{"Pieces" link "engPieces"} node.
To buy a new piece, select the desired piece type from the button underneath
the "Buy new" button, and then click the "Buy new" button. You will be asked to
place this new piece on the board. You can only place the piece on your half of
the board, ie. the upper half for player 1, the lower half for player 2.
The object of the game is to "take" both of the opposing player's "king"-type
pieces, which look like little crowns. Once this has been accomplished, the game
ends.
@endnode

@node engPieces "Xhess pieces"
There are five types of single pieces in Xhess, and they can be combined into
five different basic of groups. Basic group types may be mixed in a group to
create a hybrid group.

The single pieces are as follows:
- Basic. Looks like a little circle. Costs 20. "Taking" an opponent's Basic
gives you 6 money, but "taking" one of your own Basics costs you 3 money.
- Ortho. Looks like a square. Costs 25. "Taking" an opponent's Ortho gives you
8 money, but "taking" one of your own Orthos costs you 4 money.
- Diago. Looks like a square standing on its corner. Costs 25. "Taking" an
opponent's Diago gives you 8 money, but "taking" one of your own Diagos costs
you 4 money.
- Jumpr (pronounced "jumper"). Looks like a cross. Costs 30. "Taking" an
opponent's Jumpr gives you 10, but "taking" one of your own Jumprs costs you 5
money.
- King. Looks like a little crown. Cannot be bought. "Taking" an opponent's King
gives you 20 money, but "taking" one of your own Kings costs you 10 money.

The group types are as follows:
- Pawn. Requires at least 2 Basics. Moves one group of squares forward (towards
the enemy), or 2 groups on its initial move. Captures diagonally forward.
- Rook. Requires at least 1 Ortho. Moves any number of groups of squares either
horizontally or vertically, until it meets another group of pieces.
- Bishop. Requires at least 1 Diago. Moves any number of groups of squares
diagonally, until it meets another group of pieces.
- Knight. Requires at least 2 Jumprs. Moves in an "L" pattern: two groups of
squares in one direction, one in the other. Can jump over other groups.
- King. Requires at least 2 Kings. Moves one group of squares in any direction.
(Note that there is no such basic group type as "Queen". This can be made from
a combined Rook and Bishop.)

If you don't know where your selected piece or group of pieces could move, click
on the "Help" button so it displays a checkmark. All possible moves will be
highlighted.
Moving a group of pieces anywhere increases your money account by 1. Moving a
single piece doesn't give you any money.
@endnode

@node engRequire "Xhess requirements"
"Xhess" requires the following things:

- An Amiga computer.
- At least version 2.0 of Workbench.
- At least 340 kilobytes of free memory.
- A mouse.

An AGA chipset is recommended for prettier graphics, but is not necessary. The
program archive includes data files for both AGA and ECS chipsets.
@endnode

